by Eothasia » Sun Apr 04, 2021 1:28 am

The country maintains a socialist market economic model and implements some elements of citizen participation within the legislative process. Although it isn't clear whether the citizenry can submit petitions to the parliament to bring enact new laws, they can vote on whether or not a bill approved by the parliament is fully ratified or not. These votes take place every two months, with all pending legislation voted on. I'm interested in knowing whether or not this includes norms with force of law or all norms passed by parliament.

by Socialist Macronesia » Sun Apr 04, 2021 6:41 pm

AAN: So... in this world, in 1958, the United Nations member nations all got together after some American and Soviet troops tried to nuke to hell out of a UFO and accidentally subjected almost everyone in the squad to second degree death. So then, I guess, all the leaders of the UN member states got together and were like "cold war bad, shooty aliens good." So then they kind of just got left alone for a while until YEEHAW THE ALIENS ARE BACK and the boys (but mostly girls) got back in town. Speaking of girls, they have a bunch of Shipgirls, who are basically ships... but anime girls. I've think I've heard of this before, but I'm going to move on for a multitude of reasons, most of which that cannot be repeated in polite company.

As a side note, all of their Shipgirls are based on WWII battleships, and the organization itself is set in 1979. Unfortunately, this means the USS Ronald Reagan will likely never get to become a shipgirl. My disappointment is immeasurable and my day is ruined.

RD: Okay, there's not a whole lot to learn from this since it's not really supposed to be factual per-say, but I will say that Sayuri and Sakura may be older and younger sisters respectively, but after 200 years, apparently this still makes a difference. There's a big difference between 10 and 14, but 210 and 214 is almost nothing if you think about it. But they still think of it as a big difference.
